Installing
==========
Copy or extract the files from AmServ.lha/AmServ.lzx where
Your AmIRC is located. The files in REXX/ should be in REXX/ 


Note:
The files must be in this directory so the configfile path will
be recognized. If you use different versions/paths of where
AmIRC is located, AmServ might not find its AmServ.config file.
AmServ uses ENV:Vapor/AmIRC_LASTUSEDDIR (new in v1.32) !

@endnode


@node setting "Setting up the server."

======================================================
$VER: AmServ.amirx 1.33 (24.07'00)
Written by: Hans Petter Dalsklev © 1997-2000
EMail: hanspd@powertech.no
Homepage:  http://home.powertech.no/hanspd/amserv.html
======================================================

	@{" WHAT IS THIS       " Link "whatis"} some words about amserv and fileservers.
	@{" CONTENTS           " Link "content"} what this archive should contain.
	@{" USAGE              " Link "usage"} launching and parameters.
	@{" INSTALLING         " Link "install"} installing, simple!
	  SETTING UP AMIRC    configurating.
	@{" RUNNING IT         " Link "running"} launching it for the first time.
	@{" SHORT FAQ          " Link "faq"} a short frequently asked questions.
	@{" MORE HELP?         " Link "morehelp"} the author.
	@{" HISTORY            " Link "history"} some words from the past.


Setting up AmIRC
================
1: Load AmIRC...
2: Enter the name/nick of the server in the NICK and NAME bars.
3: Deactivate (under USERMODES)
     - "Auto open Dialog windows?"
     - "Auto accept DCC chat requests?"
     - "Auto accept DCC send requests?"
     - "Do BEEPs?"
     - "Play CTCP SOUND requests?"
4: Deactivate All logging under "SETTINGS/Logging"
   This will prevent slow dir-listings and more.
5: Press: R-AMiGA + SHIFT + R and edit the receive-path. (upload directory!!)
6: Save the config file as "AmServ.AmIRCfg" (or call it whatever u like)

Note:
- Next time u use AmServ u will only need to load the configfile and
then run the script after logging into the irc.server..

@endnode


@node running "Running it for the first time."

======================================================
$VER: AmServ.amirx 1.33 (24.07'00)
Written by: Hans Petter Dalsklev © 1997-2000
EMail: hanspd@powertech.no
Homepage:  http://home.powertech.no/hanspd/amserv.html
======================================================

	@{" WHAT IS THIS       " Link "whatis"} some words about amserv and fileservers.
	@{" CONTENTS           " Link "content"} what this archive should contain.
	@{" USAGE              " Link "usage"} launching and parameters.
	@{" INSTALLING         " Link "install"} installing, simple!
	@{" SETTING UP AMIRC   " Link "setting"} configurating.
	  RUNNING IT          launching it for the first time.
	@{" SHORT FAQ          " Link "faq"} a short frequently asked questions.
	@{" MORE HELP?         " Link "morehelp"} the author.
	@{" HISTORY            " Link "history"} some words from the past.


Running it for the first time
=============================

Executing:
----------
type: /rx amserv.amirx inside an AmIRC-client.
If this is the first time, then AmServ will open a window
with a questionary for you to fill inn.


The Questionary - with examples:
--------------------------------
This is a config-entry window that opens in Workbench. Here you
must fill inn lines. I will now explain each line of the
config-entry with examples.


1: FileServer name: MODSHEAVEN
- This is the server name, and has nothing to do with the server-nick.
Call it what you want, be free!

2: Operator nick (different from servernick): Sexyboy
- The Operator nick is important to be different from the servernick
because you cant connect to the amserv from the server it self!!
(im sorry about that, but i had to do it that way cause of the amirc-
rexx disadvantages)

3: Trigger on (ex. !mywavs) : !sexyboy
- To trigger a server meens that you tell the server to connect you.
In other words if someone now write !sexyboy in a channel (or to the
server), it will send a dcc-chat-request for him/her. The user can
either write "!sexyboy" in a channel or directly - to the server.

4: Filedir (ex. DH0:files/) : DH1:FILES/
- The filedir will be the root of the server. Users can only access
the files inside the Filedir you specify here. (ps. you can change
this at all times when connect as Operator.

5: UserFile (Enter=default) : rexx/AmServ.users
- Press enter, the system will use the default location.

6: LogFile  (Enter=default) : RAM:AmServ.log
- Press enter.. and the system will use RAM:AmServ.log as default.

7: Ratio (ex. 6 = 1:6 ) write a number: 5
- The ratio is a byte rato. That means if a USER send a file on
10000b to the server, it will give him/her 10000*ratio (here it
will be 10000*5=50000b) in credits.

8: Newuser's start credits (in bytes) : 60000
- If a new user log into your server, he/she will get 60000b
free credits.

9: Maximum allowed downloads at once pr.user : 3
- After a while of running a FileServer you notice that the
bandwidth (the speed of your modem) decreases as more users
download files at the same time. So here you can set a limit
of how many simultanious files the user can have. (here if the
user has 3 files sending, and tryes to get a file, it will be
denied.)

10: Maximum allowed uploads at once pr.user : 4
- the same as max downloads. you set the limit so that 
the users can load you with 100files at once.

11: notice users who joins the #channel? (yes/no) : yes
- On "YES" all the users who join the channel(s) which the
server is in will get a  NOTICE message. A little
notice-advertisement. (the notice-adverticement will come
longer down in this config-procedure)

12: Maximum users online at once : 5
- Sometimes, when the traffic is high, you want to keep speed
of the server transfers up. To prevent too many users, you can
choose how many you want here.

13: Hold Directory (Enter=default) : dh1:hold/
- The holddirectory is where the temporary-files will be created
while users download their hold packets. The hold system is new
in V1.1, and is a kind of: File-bag. You request files, and download
them all at once archivated later.

14: Maximum size on hold-packets (bytes) : 900000
- To prevent the system to stall too much, while users pack their
hold-dir, you can set a limit of maximum bytes in the hold dir.

15: Write a line to be used as advertisement (on-joins etc)
    You can use these keywords: %n %o %m %t %r %c %v %% %s
       %s=servername, %o=usersonline %m=maxconnections,
       %t=trigger-keyword, %r=ratio, %c=newcredits,
       %v=version-tag, %%="%" %s=OperatorNick ..
       %v=version-tag, %%="%" %s=OperatorNick ..
    Example: Trigger %n with %t. Newusers get %cb free. The ratio is %r [ %o of %m slots in use ]
    Enter Line (enter=example as default) : 
- This line will be used when the server is in file-server channels
and it advertise it self. In the advertisement it is common to tell
the server name and the trigger name. It is also nice if you mention
the newusercredits and the ratio on your fserve.. (use %r for ratio)

16: Enter the time (in secounds) between each advertising : 60
- This is the interval between each auto-advertisement the server
sends to the selected channels. Please don't set this value too
low, you will only anoy the users and probably get kicked out

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

After answering you must, if not allready done, connect AmIRC
to an irc-server.

Then run another copy of AmIRC (you can use connect-thread) and
connect it to the same irc-network (e.g DALnet). Important: The
nick must be the same as what you typed as operator-nick in the
questionary!


RULES
-----
The rules have now been terminated! There are no more
rules anymore ;-) You can (almost) f*ck up the dcc.chat and
dcc.receive windows the much you want now! .. For speed,
clean up dcc.chat/dcc.receive- window once a while..


How I do it:
============
I open a amirc as usual and chat alittle around. And then open another
AmIRC with AmServ.AmIRCfg as configfile. From there I Start the script
and iconify it!

@endnode

